Experimental

Introduction

The following are the events for the OpenJDK 21 (jdk-21.0.2+0, 19-December-2023). The events are collected from the event configuration and the source code. Visit jfreventcollector for more information. this is also the place you can contribute additional event descriptions, if you don't want to contribute them directly to the OpenJDK. The site generator lives on GitHub too.

This page is maintained by Johannes Bechberger of the SapMachine team at SAP and contributors.

Some events have fake end times / durations, these are hidden in the event description here.

Flight Recorder

DumpReason

default profiling startTime 11 17 21 22

Category: Flight Recorder

Who requested the recording and why

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrEmergencyDump.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The DumpReason event in JFR provides information about the reason for writing recording data to disk. It has two relevant fields:

  • reason: Reason for writing recording data to disk.
  • recordingId: Id of the recording that triggered the dump, or -1 if it was not related to a recording.

This event is important for profiling as it helps in understanding why a JFR dump was triggered and provides context for analyzing the recorded data.

Configuration enabled
default true
profiling true

Field Type Description
reason string Reason Reason for writing recording data to disk
recordingId int Recording Id Id of the recording that triggered the dump, or -1 if it was not related to a recording

DataLoss

default profiling startTime 11 17 21 22

Category: Flight Recorder

Data could not be copied out from a buffer, typically because of contention

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrStorage.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

  • The DataLoss event in JFR indicates the loss of data during profiling.
  • The event has two fields:
    • amount: Represents the amount of data that was lost.
    • total: Represents the total amount of data lost for the specific thread.
  • This event is relevant for profiling as it helps track and analyze any potential loss of data during profiling operations.
  • It can be used to identify and investigate any issues related to data loss, allowing for optimization and improvement of profiling performance.

Configuration enabled
default true
profiling true

Field Type Description
amount ulong: bytes Amount Amount lost data
total ulong: bytes Total Total lost amount for thread

Flush

experimental startTime duration 14 17 21 22

Category: Flight Recorder

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrRecorderService.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The Flush event in JFR is used for profiling and provides information about flushing operations. It has the following fields:

  • flushId: This field represents the identifier of the flush operation.
  • elements: This field indicates the number of elements written during the flush.
  • size: This field represents the size of the data written during the flush.

The Flush event is an experimental feature that can be used to analyze and optimize performance by understanding the impact of flushing operations on the system. It provides valuable information about the amount and size of data being written during flushing, allowing developers to identify potential bottlenecks and improve efficiency.

Configuration enabled threshold
default false 0 ns
profiling false 0 ns

Field Type Description
flushId ulong Flush Identifier
elements ulong Elements Written
size ulong: bytes Size Written

ActiveRecording

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 11 17 21 22

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/ActiveRecordingEvent.java

Category: Flight Recorder

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in ActiveRecordingEvent.java, PlatformRecorder.java, and JDKEvents.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ActiveRecording event in JFR (Java Flight Recorder) represents an active recording session and provides information about the recording settings and status. It is relevant for profiling and monitoring purposes.

The event has the following fields:

  • id: Represents the unique identifier of the recording session.
  • name: Specifies the name of the recording session.
  • destination: Indicates the destination of the recorded data.
  • disk: Indicates whether the recording is stored on disk.
  • maxAge: Specifies the maximum age of the recording before it is automatically discarded.
  • flushInterval: Specifies the interval at which data is flushed for disk-based recordings.
  • maxSize: Specifies the maximum size of the recording.
  • recordingStart: Represents the timestamp of when the recording started.
  • recordingDuration: Specifies the duration of the recording session.

The ActiveRecording event is useful for profiling and analyzing application performance because it provides insights into the settings and characteristics of an active recording session. These details can help identify performance bottlenecks, analyze resource usage, and optimize application behavior.

Configuration enabled
default true
profiling true

Field Type Description
id long Id
name string Name Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
destination string Destination Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
disk boolean 21+ To Disk
maxAge long: millis Max Age
flushInterval long: millis 14+ Flush Interval
maxSize long: bytes Max Size
recordingStart long: epochmillis Start Time
recordingDuration long: millis Recording Duration

ActiveSetting

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 11 17 21 22

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/ActiveSettingEvent.java

Category: Flight Recorder

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in EventControl.java, ActiveSettingEvent.java, PlatformRecorder.java, and JDKEvents.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ActiveSettingEvent is an event in the Java Flight Recorder (JFR) system that captures information about a recording setting. It is relevant to profiling as it allows profiling tools to track changes in recording settings during the execution of a Java application.

The event has the following fields:

  • id: Event Id, which represents the identifier of the setting being modified.
  • name: Setting Name, which indicates the name of the setting being modified.
  • value: Setting Value, which represents the new value of the setting being modified.

By analyzing ActiveSettingEvent events, profiling tools can understand which settings were modified and their corresponding values at a specific time, providing valuable insights into how the application's behavior may have been influenced.

Configuration enabled
default true
profiling true

Field Type Description
id long Event Id
name string Setting Name
value string Setting Value

JVM

JVMInformation

default profiling startTime duration end chunk 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine

Description of JVM and the Java application

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The JVMInformation event in JFR (Java Flight Recorder) provides information about the JVM (Java Virtual Machine) and its runtime environment. It is relevant to profiling because it captures important details about the JVM and its configuration, which can help in understanding the performance and behavior of the application being profiled. The event includes the following fields:

  • jvmName: The name of the JVM.
  • jvmVersion: The version of the JVM.
  • jvmArguments: The command line arguments passed to the JVM.
  • jvmFlags: The settings file arguments used by the JVM.
  • javaArguments: The arguments passed to the Java application.
  • jvmStartTime: The timestamp indicating when the JVM was started.
  • pid: The process identifier of the JVM.

By analyzing the data in these fields, developers can gain insights into the JVM's behavior and make informed decisions to optimize performance, identify potential issues, and troubleshoot problems in the application.

Configuration enabled period
default true beginChunk
profiling true beginChunk

Field Type Description
jvmName string JVM Name
jvmVersion string JVM Version
jvmArguments string JVM Command Line Arguments
jvmFlags string JVM Settings File Arguments
javaArguments string Java Application Arguments
jvmStartTime long: epochmillis JVM Start Time
pid long Process Identifier

InitialSystemProperty

default profiling startTime end chunk 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine

System Property at JVM start

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The InitialSystemProperty event in JFR represents the initial system properties set during JVM startup.

  • key field represents the key of the system property.
  • value field represents the value of the system property.

This event is useful for profiling as it provides information about the initial system properties set, which can be valuable for understanding the JVM configuration and its impact on application performance.

JVM: Class Loading

ClassLoad

startTime duration eventThread stackTrace 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Class Loading

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in systemDictionary.hpp, systemDictionaryShared.cpp, and systemDictionary.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ClassLoad event in Java Flight Recorder (JFR) captures information about class loading in the JVM. It is relevant to profiling as it provides insights into how classes are loaded and by which class loaders.

Fields of the ClassLoad event:

  • loadedClass: The class that has been loaded.
  • definingClassLoader: The class loader that defined the loaded class.
  • initiatingClassLoader: The class loader that initiated the loading process.

By analyzing the ClassLoad event, profiling tools can gather information about the class loading behavior and identify any performance bottlenecks or issues related to class loading in the application.

Configuration enabled stackTrace threshold
default false true 0 ms
profiling false true 0 ms

Field Type Description
loadedClass Class Loaded Class Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
definingClassLoader ClassLoader Defining Class Loader Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
initiatingClassLoader ClassLoader Initiating Class Loader Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.

ClassDefine

startTime eventThread stackTrace 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Class Loading

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in systemDictionary.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ClassDefine event in JFR is relevant to profiling as it provides information about the definition of a class. Some key points about this event are:

  • The event has two fields: definedClass and definingClassLoader.
  • The definedClass field represents the class that has been defined.
  • The definingClassLoader field represents the class loader responsible for defining the class.
  • The event can be used to track and analyze the class loading process in a profiling session.
  • It provides insights into the relationship between class loaders and the classes they define.
  • By analyzing this event, profiling tools can identify the sequence and timing of class definitions, helping to optimize class loading and improve overall performance.

Configuration enabled stackTrace
default false true
profiling false true

Field Type Description
definedClass Class Defined Class Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
definingClassLoader ClassLoader Defining Class Loader Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.

ClassRedefinition

default profiling startTime 15 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Class Loading

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jvmtiRedefineClasses.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ClassRedefinition event in JFR represents the redefinition of a class during runtime.

Fields of the ClassRedefinition event:

  • redefinedClass: Represents the class that has been redefined.
  • classModificationCount: Stores the number of times the class has been modified.
  • redefinitionId: Uniquely identifies the class redefinition.

Relevance to profiling:

  • This event is relevant for profiling as it allows monitoring and tracking of class redefinitions during runtime.
  • Changes to classes can impact the performance or behavior of an application, and by profiling the ClassRedefinition event, developers can analyze the impact and make necessary optimizations or fixes.
  • Profiling the classModificationCount field can provide insights into the frequency of class modifications and help identify potential areas for improvement or optimization.

Configuration enabled
default true
profiling true

Field Type Description
redefinedClass Class Redefined Class Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
classModificationCount int Class Modification Count The number of times the class has changed
redefinitionId ulong Class Redefinition Id

RedefineClasses

default profiling startTime duration eventThread stackTrace 15 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Class Loading

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jvmtiEnv.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The RedefineClasses event in JFR is used to redefine classes during the profiling process. It allows you to modify the definitions of existing classes at runtime.

The event has the following fields:

  • classCount: the number of classes being redefined
  • redefinitionId: the unique identifier for the class redefinition

The RedefineClasses event is relevant to profiling because it enables you to dynamically modify class definitions, allowing for more flexible and targeted profiling.

Configuration enabled stackTrace threshold

The RetransformClasses event in JFR is used for profiling and it is relevant to the fields classCount and redefinitionId.

  • classCount: This field represents the number of classes that are being retransformed.
  • redefinitionId: This field holds the unique identifier for the class redefinition operation.

The RetransformClasses event is used to initiate the retransformation of a set of classes in the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) without restarting the JVM. This event allows developers to modify and redefine classes at runtime, enabling dynamic code changes and profiling of the modified classes.

By monitoring the RetransformClasses event and analyzing its fields, profiling tools can track and analyze the number of classes being retransformed and identify the specific redefinition operation using the redefinitionId field. This information can be used to gather insights into the performance and behavior of dynamically modified classes in the JVM.

JVM: Code Cache

CodeCacheFull

default profiling startTime eventThread 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Code Cache

A code heap is full, this leads to disabling the compiler

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in codeCache.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The CodeCacheFull event in JFR is generated when a code heap in the code cache becomes full. It is relevant to profiling as it provides information about the state of the code cache and helps in understanding the memory usage and performance of the code cache.

Fields of the CodeCacheFull event:

  • codeBlobType: Indicates the type of code heap that is full.
  • startAddress: The starting address of the code heap.
  • commitedTopAddress: The committed top address of the code heap.
  • reservedTopAddress: The reserved top address of the code heap.
  • entryCount: The number of entries in the code heap.
  • methodCount: The number of methods in the code heap.
  • adaptorCount: The number of adaptors in the code heap.
  • unallocatedCapacity: The amount of unallocated capacity in the code heap.
  • fullCount: The number of times the code heap has become full.
  • codeCacheMaxCapacity: The maximum capacity of the code cache.

By analyzing the CodeCacheFull event and its fields, developers can gain insights into the memory usage and performance of the code cache, identify potential bottlenecks, and optimize the usage of the code cache to improve overall application performance.

Configuration enabled
default true
profiling true

Field Type Description
codeBlobType CodeBlobType Code Heap Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
startAddress ulong: address Start Address
commitedTopAddress ulong: address Commited Top
reservedTopAddress ulong: address Reserved Top
entryCount int Entries
methodCount int Methods
adaptorCount int Adaptors
unallocatedCapacity ulong: bytes Unallocated
fullCount int Full Count
codeCacheMaxCapacity ulong: bytes 17+ Code Cache Maximum Capacity

By analyzing these fields, developers can gain insights into the code cache's memory usage, identify any potential issues or bottlenecks, and optimize the performance of the application.

CodeCacheConfiguration

default profiling startTime end chunk 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Code Cache

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The CodeCacheConfiguration event in JFR provides information about the configuration and size of the code cache.

  • initialSize: The initial size of the code cache.
  • reservedSize: The maximum reserved size of the code cache.
  • nonNMethodSize: The size of the code cache dedicated to non-nmethod (non-compiled) code.
  • profiledSize: The size of the code cache used for profiled (optimized) code.
  • nonProfiledSize: The size of the code cache used for non-profiled (interpreted) code.
  • expansionSize: The size of each code cache expansion.
  • minBlockLength: The minimum length of a code cache block.
  • startAddress: The starting address of the code cache.
  • reservedTopAddress: The highest reserved address of the code cache.

This event can be used for profiling to understand the size and configuration of the code cache, which is important for optimizing code execution in Java applications.

default true beginChunk

JITRestart

default profiling startTime eventThread 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Compiler

Restart of the JIT compilers after they were stopped

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in codeCache.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The JITRestart event in JFR stands for Just-In-Time Restart. This event is relevant to profiling as it provides information about the restart of the JIT compiler in the code cache.

The JITRestart event has the following fields:

  • freedMemory: Represents the amount of memory freed during the restart of the JIT compiler. It indicates the memory that was previously occupied by compiled code that has been flushed.
  • codeCacheMaxCapacity: Indicates the maximum capacity of the code cache. This field provides information about the size limit of the code cache.

The JITRestart event is useful for profiling as it allows developers to track and analyze the impact of JIT compiler restarts on code cache usage. By monitoring the freedMemory field, developers can gain insight into the amount of memory that is being reclaimed and measure the effectiveness of the JIT compiler in optimizing code execution. Additionally, the codeCacheMaxCapacity field helps in understanding the limits of code caching and can aid in capacity planning and optimization.

default true
profiling true

Field Type Description
freedMemory ulong: bytes Freed Memory
codeCacheMaxCapacity ulong: bytes Code Cache Maximum Capacity

Compilation

default profiling startTime duration eventThread 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Compiler

Results of method compilation attempts

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in EventProvider.java, EmptyEventProvider.java, compilerEvent.hpp, compileBroker.cpp, and compilerEvent.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The Compilation event in Java Flight Recorder (JFR) is a type of event that is relevant to profiling. It provides information about the compilation of a method during runtime.

Fields of the Compilation event include:

  • compileId: Identifier for the compilation
  • compiler: Compile type used for the compilation
  • method: Method being compiled
  • compileLevel: Level of the compilation
  • succeeded: Flag indicating if the compilation succeeded
  • isOsr: Flag indicating if the compilation is for on-stack replacement
  • codeSize: Size of the compiled code
  • inlinedBytes: Size of the inlined code

By analyzing the Compilation events, developers can gather information about the performance of the JIT compiler and understand how methods are being compiled during runtime. This can help in identifying performance bottlenecks and optimizing code.

CompilerPhase

default profiling startTime duration eventThread 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Compiler

Describes various phases of the compilation process like inlining or string optimization related phases

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jvmciCompilerToVM.cpp, compile.cpp, JFR.java, compilerEvent.hpp, and compilerEvent.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The CompilerPhase event in JFR is used for profiling compiler phases during the compilation process. It provides information about the different phases that the compiler goes through.

The relevant fields of the CompilerPhase event are:

  • phase: Represents the specific compiler phase being executed.
  • compileId: Identifies the current compilation unit.
  • phaseLevel: Indicates the nesting level of the compiler phase.

By analyzing the phase field, the profiler can determine which specific phase is being executed during the compilation process. The compileId field helps identify the specific compilation unit, while the phaseLevel field provides information about the nesting level of the phase.

This event is particularly useful for understanding the performance and behavior of the compiler and can provide insights into potential optimizations or bottlenecks in the compilation process.

CompilerInlining

startTime eventThread 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Compiler / Optimization

Describes the result of a method inlining attempt

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in c1_GraphBuilder.cpp, jvmciCompilerToVM.cpp, JFR.java, bytecodeInfo.cpp, compilerEvent.hpp, and compilerEvent.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The CompilerInlining event in JFR records information about inlining decisions made by the compiler during the profiling process. It is useful for understanding how the compiler optimizes code by inlining methods.

Fields:

  • compileId: Identifier of the compilation unit.
  • caller: The method making the inlining decision.
  • callee: The method being inlined.
  • succeeded: Indicates whether the inlining was successful or not.
  • message: Additional information about the inlining decision.
  • bci: The bytecode index where the inlining decision occurred.

This event can be used to analyze the effectiveness of inlining decisions and identify potential performance bottlenecks in the code. By looking at the caller and callee methods, the impact of inlining on the execution can be evaluated. The succeeded field indicates if the inlining was beneficial or not. The message field provides further details about the inlining decision, which can help in understanding the reasons behind the decision.

Overall, the CompilerInlining event is an important event for profiling and optimizing code, as it provides insights into how the compiler transforms and optimizes the program by inlining methods.

default false
profiling false

Deoptimization

default profiling startTime eventThread stackTrace 14 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Compiler

Describes the detection of an uncommon situation in a compiled method which may lead to deoptimization of the method

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in deoptimization.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The Deoptimization event in JFR (Java Flight Recorder) captures information about deoptimization that occurs during program execution. Deoptimization is the process of undoing optimization in the JVM (Java Virtual Machine) when certain conditions are not met. Here is the meaning and relevance of the event to profiling and its fields:

  • compileId: The identifier of the compilation that is being deoptimized.
  • compiler: The compiler used for the deoptimized compilation.
  • method: The method being deoptimized.
  • lineNumber: The line number in the source code where the deoptimized bytecode resides.
  • bci: The bytecode index of the deoptimized bytecode.
  • instruction: The instruction being deoptimized.
  • reason: The reason for the deoptimization, such as constraint failure or transfer to interpreter.
  • action: The action taken during deoptimization, such as recompiling or reverting to interpreter execution.

The Deoptimization event provides valuable information for profiling and analyzing the performance of the JVM and the optimized code. It helps identify the specific methods and instructions that are being affected by deoptimization, allowing developers to optimize their code or investigate potential issues. By examining the deoptimization reasons and actions, developers can gain insights into the behavior of the optimized code and make informed decisions for optimization and performance tuning.

Configuration enabled stackTrace
default true false
profiling true true

Field Type Description
compileId int Compilation Identifier
compiler CompilerType Compiler Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
method Method Method Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
lineNumber int Line Number
bci int Bytecode Index
instruction Bytecode Instruction Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
reason DeoptimizationReason Reason Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
action DeoptimizationAction Action Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.

CompilerStatistics

default profiling startTime every chunk 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Compiler

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

  • The CompilerStatistics event in JFR provides information about various statistics related to method compilation in the JVM.
  • The event has fields such as compileCount, bailoutCount, invalidatedCount, osrCompileCount, standardCompileCount, osrBytesCompiled, standardBytesCompiled, nmethodsSize, nmethodCodeSize, peakTimeSpent, and totalTimeSpent.
  • These fields indicate the number of compiled methods, the number of bailouts during compilation, the number of invalidated compilations, the number of OSR (On-Stack Replacement) compilations, the number of standard compilations, the number of OSR bytes compiled, the number of standard bytes compiled, the size of the compilation resulting in size and the size of the resulting code, the peak time spent on compilation, and the total time spent on compilation.
  • This event is relevant for profiling the performance and efficiency of the JVM's method compilation process.
  • By analyzing the values of these fields, developers can gain insights into the efficiency of the JVM's compilation process and identify potential areas for optimization.

default true 1000 ms
profiling true 1000 ms

osrBytesCompiled ulong: bytes OSR Bytes Compiled
standardBytesCompiled ulong: bytes Standard Bytes Compiled
nmethodsSize ulong: bytes Compilation Resulting Size
nmethodCodeSize ulong: bytes Compilation Resulting Code Size
peakTimeSpent long: millis Peak Time

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The CompilerConfiguration event in JFR provides information about the compiler configuration in the JVM. It is relevant for profiling purposes as it gives insight into the number of compiler threads and the usage of tiered compilation and dynamic compiler threads.

  • threadCount: Represents the number of compiler threads used.
  • tieredCompilation: Indicates whether tiered compilation is enabled or disabled.
  • dynamicCompilerThreadCount: Indicates whether the JVM uses a dynamic number of compiler threads.

Profiling tools can use this event to analyze the performance of the compiler and fine-tune the compiler configuration for optimal performance.

The SyncOnValueBasedClass event in JFR is used to handle notifications when synchronizing on value-based classes. It is relevant for profiling because it allows developers to identify instances where synchronization is being performed on value-based classes within their code.

The event has one field:

  • valueBasedClass: Represents the value-based class on which synchronization is being performed.

By analyzing this event, developers can gain insights into synchronization patterns and potentially identify areas where synchronization on value-based classes can be optimized or eliminated. This can help improve performance and efficiency in multi-threaded applications.

HeapDump

default profiling startTime duration eventThread stackTrace 15 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Diagnostics

Information about a successfully written Java heap dump

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in heapDumper.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The HeapDump event in JFR is used for profiling and provides information about heap dumps. It has the following fields:

  • destination: The path where the heap dump is saved.
  • size: The size of the heap dump in bytes.
  • gcBeforeDump: Indicates whether a garbage collection was performed before the heap dump.
  • onOutOfMemoryError: Indicates whether the heap dump was triggered by an Out of Memory Error.
  • overwrite: Indicates whether the heap dump overwrites a previously existing file.
  • compression: The compression level applied to the heap dump, using gzip compression if a level larger than 0 is provided.

The event is relevant for profiling as it allows users to analyze the memory usage of an application and identify potential memory leaks or other memory-related issues.

Configuration enabled stackTrace threshold
default true true 0 ns
profiling true true 0 ns

Field Type Description
destination string Destination Path of the Dump
size long Size
gcBeforeDump boolean GC Before Dump
onOutOfMemoryError boolean Heap Dump on Out of Memory Error
overwrite boolean 21+ Overwrite Heap dump overwrites previous file location if it exists
compression int 21+ Compression Level Compression level of the dump, if larger than 0 we use gzip compression with this level

JavaAgent

default profiling startTime end chunk 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Diagnostics

A Java programming language agent making use of the java.lang.instrument package for instrumenting programs running on the JVM

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The JavaAgent event in JFR (Java Flight Recorder) represents a Java agent that is attached to the JVM during runtime. It provides the following fields:

  • name: The name of the Java agent
  • options: The options that were used when the agent was attached
  • dynamic: Indicates whether the agent was attached dynamically during runtime
  • initializationTime: The time when the JVM initialized the agent
  • initializationDuration: The duration of executing the initialization method of the agent

This event is relevant to profiling as it allows you to track and analyze the behavior of different Java agents that are attached to the JVM. It provides insights into the configuration and initialization details of these agents, which can help in understanding their impact on application performance and behavior.

Configuration enabled period
default true endChunk
profiling true endChunk

Field Type Description
name string Name
options string Options
dynamic boolean Dynamic If the agent attached to the JVM dynamically during runtime, i.e. not at startup
initializationTime Ticks Initialization Time The time the JVM initialized the agent
initializationDuration Tickspan Initialization Duration The duration of executing the initialization method, either premain or agentmain

NativeAgent

default profiling startTime end chunk 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Diagnostics

A native programming language agent making use of the JVMTI interface used by development, profiling and monitoring tools

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The NativeAgent event in JFR represents a native agent attached to the JVM during runtime. It provides information about the properties and initialization of the native agent. This event is relevant for profiling and monitoring the behavior of native agents within the JVM.

Fields of the NativeAgent event include:

  • name: Name of the native agent
  • options: Options used to attach the native agent
  • dynamic: Indicates whether the native agent was attached dynamically during runtime
  • initializationTime: The time when the JVM initialized the native agent
  • initializationDuration: The duration of executing the JVMTI VMInit event callback or Agent_OnAttach for dynamically loaded agents
  • path: The path of the native agent library

This event allows profiling tools to gather information about native agents and their impact on the JVM's behavior and performance. It can be used to identify and analyze the behavior of certain native agents, their initialization time, and the options used to attach them to the JVM.

Configuration enabled period
default true endChunk
profiling true endChunk

Field Type Description
name string Name
options string Options
dynamic boolean Dynamic If the library attached to the JVM dynamically during runtime, i.e. not at startup
initializationTime Ticks Initialization Time The time the JVM initialized the agent
initializationDuration Tickspan Initialization Duration The duration of executing the JVMTI VMInit event callback. If no VMInit callback is specified, the duration is 0. For a dynamically loaded agent, it is the duration of executing the call to Agent_OnAttach.
path string Path The path of the library

The IntFlagChanged event in JFR represents a change in the value of an integer flag in the JVM. It captures the following information:

  • name: the name of the flag that was changed
  • oldValue: the previous value of the flag
  • newValue: the new value of the flag
  • origin: the origin of the flag change (e.g., user, ergonomics, command-line)

This event is relevant for profiling because it allows for monitoring changes to integer flags in the JVM. By analyzing the captured events, it is possible to understand how different flag values impact the performance and behavior of the JVM. This information can be useful for troubleshooting, optimizing system performance, and identifying potential performance bottlenecks.

GarbageCollection

default profiling startTime duration eventThread 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / GC / Collector

Garbage collection performed by the JVM

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in gcTraceSend.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The GarbageCollection event in JFR provides information about garbage collection operations in Java applications. It is relevant for profiling purposes and can be used to analyze garbage collection behavior and performance. The event includes the following fields:

  • gcId: Identifier for the garbage collection event
  • name: Name of the garbage collector
  • cause: The reason for triggering the garbage collection
  • sumOfPauses: Sum of all the times Java execution was paused during the garbage collection
  • longestPause: Duration of the longest individual pause during the garbage collection

By analyzing these fields, profiling tools can gain insights into garbage collection patterns, identify potential bottlenecks, and optimize memory management in Java applications.

Configuration enabled threshold
default true 0 ms
profiling true 0 ms

Field Type Description
gcId uint GC Identifier
name GCName Name The name of the Garbage Collector
cause GCCause Cause The reason for triggering this Garbage Collection
sumOfPauses Tickspan Sum of Pauses Sum of all the times in which Java execution was paused during the garbage collection
longestPause Tickspan Longest Pause Longest individual pause during the garbage collection

The ZYoungGarbageCollection event in Java Flight Recorder (JFR) represents a minor garbage collection that occurs in the Z Garbage Collector (ZGC).

Relevance to profiling:

  • The event provides information about the garbage collection process in the ZGC, which is useful for profiling and understanding memory management.
  • It allows profiling tools to capture metrics and analyze the behavior of the minor garbage collections.
  • The event can be used to track and optimize the tenuring threshold, which determines when objects are promoted from the young generation to the old generation.

Fields of the ZYoungGarbageCollection event:

  • gcId: Identifier of the garbage collection event.
  • tenuringThreshold: The current value of the tenuring threshold for the young generation.

This event helps in analyzing and fine-tuning garbage collection behavior and memory management in Java applications that use the ZGC.

default profiling startTime duration end chunk 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / GC / Configuration

The configuration of the garbage collector

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The GCConfiguration event in JFR represents the configuration settings of the garbage collector. It is used for profiling and has the following relevant fields:

  • youngCollector: The garbage collector used for the young generation.
  • oldCollector: The garbage collector used for the old generation.
  • parallelGCThreads: Number of parallel threads to use for garbage collection.
  • concurrentGCThreads: Number of concurrent threads to use for garbage collection.
  • usesDynamicGCThreads: Indicates whether a dynamic number of GC threads are used or not.
  • isExplicitGCConcurrent: Indicates whether System.gc() is concurrent or not.
  • isExplicitGCDisabled: Indicates whether System.gc() will cause a garbage collection or not.
  • pauseTarget: Target for GC pauses.
  • gcTimeRatio: Target for runtime vs garbage collection time.

These fields provide information about the garbage collector's behavior and configuration, which can be useful for optimizing and tuning the garbage collection process.

Configuration enabled period
default true everyChunk
profiling true everyChunk

Field Type Description

oldCollector GCName Old Garbage Collector The garbage collector used for the old generation
parallelGCThreads uint Parallel GC Threads Number of parallel threads to use for garbage collection
concurrentGCThreads uint Concurrent GC Threads Number of concurrent threads to use for garbage collection
usesDynamicGCThreads boolean Uses Dynamic GC Threads Whether a dynamic number of GC threads are used or not
isExplicitGCConcurrent boolean Concurrent Explicit GC Whether System.gc() is concurrent or not
isExplicitGCDisabled boolean Disabled Explicit GC Whether System.gc() will cause a garbage collection or not
pauseTarget long: millis Pause Target Target for GC pauses
gcTimeRatio uint GC Time Ratio Target for runtime vs garbage collection time

GCSurvivorConfiguration

default profiling startTime duration end chunk 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / GC / Configuration

The configuration of the survivors of garbage collection

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The GCSurvivorConfiguration event in JFR (Java Flight Recorder) provides information about the configuration of the survivor area in the garbage collector.

  • maxTenuringThreshold: Specifies the upper limit for the age of objects to keep in the survivor area. This determines the number of minor garbage collections an object must survive before being promoted to the old generation.
  • initialTenuringThreshold: Specifies the initial age limit for objects in the survivor area. Objects younger than this threshold are considered young and will not be moved to the old generation.

This event can be used for profiling purposes to understand and analyze the behavior of the garbage collector and how it manages objects in the survivor area.

Configuration enabled period
default true beginChunk
profiling true beginChunk

Field Type Description

initialTenuringThreshold ubyte Initial Tenuring Threshold Initial age limit for how old objects to keep in survivor area

The GCTLABConfiguration event in JFR represents the TLAB (Thread Local Allocation Buffers) configuration information. TLABs are used to allocate memory without contention among threads. The event has the following fields:

This event can be useful for profiling and understanding the memory allocation behavior of an application. It provides insights into the TLAB configuration and usage, enabling optimization of memory allocation.

The GCHeapConfiguration event in JFR provides information about the configuration of the garbage-collected heap. This event is relevant for profiling and analyzing the memory usage of an application. The fields of the event provide the following information:

  • initialSize: The initial size of the heap

  • objectAlignment: The alignment (in bytes) of objects on the heap
  • heapAddressBits: The size (in bits) of the heap's address space

These fields can be used to analyze the heap size and configuration of an application, which can help in understanding memory usage patterns and optimizing the allocation and utilization of memory.

JVM: GC: Detailed

ZThreadDebug

internal startTime duration eventThread 18 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / GC / Detailed

Temporary latency measurements used during development and debugging of ZGC

Only valid for the ZGC.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in zTracer.inline.hpp, zTracer.cpp, xTracer.inline.hpp, and xTracer.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ZThreadDebug event in JFR is an internal event used for profiling in HotSpot. It is relevant for understanding the execution of threads during garbage collection.

Meaning and relevance of the event:

  • The gcId field represents the identifier of the garbage collection operation.
  • The name field stores the name of the thread being profiled.
  • This event provides information about the execution of threads during garbage collection, allowing for profiling and analysis of thread behavior.

To use the ZThreadDebug event for profiling:

  • Enable JFR and the EventZThreadDebug event.
  • The ZTracer::report_thread_debug method is called with the thread name, start time, and end time.
  • The event is then sent with the required parameters using the send_thread_debug method.
  • The event is committed and can be analyzed and used for profiling purposes.

Field Type Description
gcId uint GC Identifier
name string Name The name of the GC runner

The G1MMU JFR event is used for profiling and provides information about the time spent on garbage collection (GC) during a time slice. Here are the fields of the event:

  • gcId: The identifier of the GC event.
  • timeSlice: The time slice used to calculate the MMU (MilliUnits).
  • gcTime: The time stopped because of GC during the last time slice (MilliUnits).
  • pauseTarget: The maximum time allowed to be spent on GC during the last time slice (MilliUnits).

This event can be used to analyze the efficiency of Garbage Collection and identify performance bottlenecks in the application. By monitoring the timeSlice, gcTime, and comparing it with the pauseTarget, developers can gain insights into GC behavior and optimize their application accordingly.

The EvacuationInformation event in JFR provides information about the garbage collection evacuation process in G1GC. It can be used for profiling purposes in the following ways:

  • gcId: Represents the identifier for the current garbage collection.
  • cSetRegions: Contains the collection set regions used during the evacuation process.
  • cSetUsedBefore: Indicates the memory usage in the collection set regions before the garbage collection.
  • cSetUsedAfter: Represents the memory usage in the collection set regions after the garbage collection.
  • allocationRegions: Specifies the regions selected as allocation regions during the evacuation, including survivor and old space regions.
  • allocationRegionsUsedBefore: Indicates the memory usage in the allocation regions before the garbage collection.
  • allocationRegionsUsedAfter: Represents the memory usage in the allocation regions after the garbage collection.
  • bytesCopied: Provides information about the total number of bytes copied during the evacuation process.
  • regionsFreed: Indicates the number of regions freed during the garbage collection.

Overall, the EvacuationInformation event enables profiling and analysis of memory usage, memory copy operations, and region management during the evacuation phase of G1GC garbage collection.

The G1BasicIHOP event is a JFR (Java Flight Recorder) event used for profiling in the G1 garbage collector. It provides information about the incremental heap occupancy (IHOP) in the G1 old generation during mixed garbage collection. The event includes the following fields:

  • gcId: The identifier of the garbage collection event.
  • threshold: The current IHOP threshold.
  • thresholdPercentage: The current IHOP threshold as a percentage of the old generation.
  • targetOccupancy: The target old generation occupancy to reach at the start of mixed garbage collection.
  • currentOccupancy: The current old generation occupancy.
  • recentMutatorAllocationSize: The size of the mutator allocation during the most recent interval.
  • recentMutatorDuration: The duration of the mutator operation in the most recent interval.
  • recentAllocationRate: The allocation rate of the mutator in bytes per second during the most recent interval.
  • lastMarkingDuration: The duration from the end of the last concurrent start to the first mixed garbage collection.

This event can be used to analyze the behavior and efficiency of the G1 garbage collector by monitoring the IHOP threshold and tracking the occupancy of the old generation. The fields provide insights into the mutator behavior, allocation rates, and marking durations, which can help optimize the garbage collection process.

PromoteObjectInNewPLAB

profiling startTime eventThread 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / GC / Detailed

Appearing in: G1GC, ParallelGC

Missing in: SerialGC, ShenandoahGC, ZGC

Object survived scavenge and was copied to a new Promotion Local Allocation Buffer (PLAB). Supported GCs are Parallel Scavenge, G1 and CMS with Parallel New. Due to promotion being done in parallel an object might be reported multiple times as the GC threads race to copy all objects.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in gcTraceSend.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The PromoteObjectInNewPLAB event in JFR is relevant for profiling and provides information about objects that are promoted from the young generation to the old generation in the garbage collector.

The event has the following fields:

  • gcId: Signifies the GC during which the object was promoted.
  • objectClass: Represents the class of the promoted object.
  • objectSize: Indicates the size of the promoted object.
  • tenuringAge: Specifies the tenuring age of the object, which is the number of scavenge cycles it has survived.
  • tenured: Represents whether the object was promoted to the old generation or to a survivor space.
  • plabSize: Indicates the size of the allocated Parallel Load Balancing (PLAB) to which the object was copied.

This event can be used to gather information about objects that survive in the young generation and are promoted to the old generation. It can help in analyzing memory usage patterns and understanding the efficiency of the garbage collector.

Overall, the PromoteObjectInNewPLAB event provides insights into object promotion during garbage collection, which can be valuable for profiling and optimizing memory management in Java applications.

Configuration enabled
default false
profiling true

Field Type Description
gcId uint GC Identifier Identifier signifying GC during which the object was promoted
objectClass Class Object Class Class of promoted object
objectSize ulong: bytes Object Size Size of promoted object
tenuringAge uint Object Tenuring Age Tenuring age of a surviving object before being copied. The tenuring age of an object is a value between 0-15 and is incremented each scavenge the object survives. Newly allocated objects have tenuring age 0.
tenured boolean Tenured True if object was promoted to Old space, otherwise the object was aged and copied to a Survivor space
plabSize ulong: bytes PLAB Size Size of the allocated PLAB to which the object was copied

Category: Java Virtual Machine / GC / Detailed

Missing in: ParallelGC, ShenandoahGC, ZGC

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in ageTableTracer.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The TenuringDistribution event in JFR represents the distribution of objects across different age groups during garbage collection. Here is its relevance to profiling and its fields:

  • The gcId field represents the identifier of the garbage collection event.
  • The age field represents the age group of the objects.
  • The size field represents the size of the objects in the age group.

Profiling with TenuringDistribution event:

  • By analyzing the age and size fields, we can understand the distribution of objects in different age groups during garbage collection.
  • This information helps in profiling the behavior of objects and their longevity in the Java heap.
  • It helps identify potential optimizations, such as adjusting the tenuring threshold or optimizing generational garbage collection algorithms.

To use the TenuringDistribution event for profiling:

  • Check if the event is enabled using the is_tenuring_distribution_event_enabled method.
  • If enabled, create a new instance of EventTenuringDistribution.
  • Set the gcId, age, and size fields accordingly.
  • Call the commit method to send the event for profiling and analysis.

The G1HeapRegionTypeChange event in JFR represents a change in the type of a G1 heap region during garbage collection. It is relevant for profiling as it provides information about the evolution of heap regions during the garbage collection process. The event has the following fields:

  • index: The index of the heap region.
  • from: The previous type of the heap region.
  • to: The new type of the heap region.
  • start: The starting address of the heap region.
  • used: The amount of memory used in the heap region.

By monitoring this event, the profiler can track the transitions of heap regions from one type to another, providing insights into the behavior of the garbage collector and the usage patterns of the application's memory space.

The ObjectCount event in JFR provides information about the count and size of objects that have been processed by a garbage collector. This event is relevant for profiling and understanding memory usage in an application.

Key points about the ObjectCount event:

  • gcId: It represents the identifier of the garbage collector, which can help in tracking the specific garbage collection process.
  • objectClass: It refers to the class of the objects that have been processed by the garbage collector.
  • count: It indicates the number of objects of a specific class that have been processed.
  • totalSize: It represents the total size in bytes of the processed objects.

By analyzing these fields in the ObjectCount event, one can gain insights into the memory usage patterns and identify potential memory leaks or areas of improvement in the application. This information can be used for profiling and optimizing memory utilization.

Allocation of a ZPage

Auto generated description experimental

The ZPageAllocation event is used for profiling in JFR (Java Flight Recorder) to track the allocation of pages in the Z Garbage Collector (ZGC). Here's a concise explanation of the event and its fields:

  • type: The type of the allocated page (e.g., young or old).
  • size: The size of the allocated page.
  • flushed: The number of flushed pages after the allocation.
  • committed: The number of committed pages after the allocation.
  • segments: The number of memory segments in the allocated page.
  • nonBlocking: Indicates whether the allocation was performed in a non-blocking manner.

This event provides information about the allocation process in the ZGC, including the type and size of the allocated page, the number of flushed and committed pages, the number of memory segments, and whether the allocation was non-blocking. It can be used for profiling and analyzing the behavior of the ZGC to optimize performance and memory management.

ZUncommit

default profiling startTime duration eventThread 15 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / GC / Detailed

Uncommitting of memory

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in zUncommitter.cpp, and xUncommitter.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ZUncommit event in JFR is related to profiling and it is used for tracking uncommitted memory in the Z garbage collector.

Fields of the ZUncommit event include:

  • uncommitted: the amount of uncommitted memory in bytes.

To use this event for profiling, the following steps can be followed:

  1. Create an instance of the ZUncommitter class, providing a ZPageAllocator object.
  2. Call the wait method on the ZUncommitter instance to wait for the event to occur.
  3. Inside the run_thread method of the ZUncommitter class, create an instance of the EventZUncommit event.
  4. Iterate over the uncommitted memory chunks using the should_continue method and uncommit each chunk using the _page_allocator->uncommit method.
  5. If any memory was uncommitted, update the statistics by incrementing the ZCounterUncommit counter and log information about the amount uncommitted.
  6. Finally, send the event using the event.commit method.

Configuration enabled threshold
default true 0 ms
profiling true 0 ms

Field Type Description
uncommitted ulong: bytes Uncommitted

  • The from field indicates the previous state of the region.
  • The to field indicates the new state of the region.
  • The start field represents the starting memory address of the region.
  • The used field indicates the amount of memory used in the region.

This event can be used for profiling purposes, such as monitoring the allocation and deallocation patterns of Shenandoah heap regions in order to identify any potential performance issues or memory usage patterns. By analyzing the state changes recorded in this event, developers can gain insight into the overall behavior and efficiency of the Shenandoah garbage collector.

The GCLocker event in JFR provides information about the GC locker for profiling purposes. The event has two fields:

  • lockCount: Indicates the number of Java threads that are in a critical section when the GC locker is started. This field helps identify the impact of locking on garbage collection performance.

  • stallCount: Represents the number of Java threads that are stalled by the GC locker. This field helps identify any potential performance issues caused by thread stalls during garbage collection.

By analyzing the values of these fields in the GCLocker event, developers can gain insights into the concurrency and performance impact of the GC locker in the given JVM application.

Configuration enabled stackTrace threshold
default true true 1 s
profiling true true 100 ms

Field Type Description

stallCount uint Stall Count The number of Java threads stalled by the GC locker

The JFR event GCHeapSummary provides information about the summary of the garbage collector (GC) heap during garbage collection. It is relevant for profiling and can be used to understand memory usage patterns and optimize memory management in Java applications.

The event has the following fields:

  • gcId: An identifier for the garbage collection.
  • when: Indicates the timing of the event.
  • heapSpace: A summary of the virtual space used by the heap, including the start and end addresses, committed size, and reserved size.

By analyzing the data captured in the GCHeapSummary event, developers can gain insights into the memory usage of their application during garbage collection. This information can help identify memory leaks, optimize garbage collection settings, and improve the overall performance and efficiency of the application.

The PSHeapSummary event in JFR provides a summary of the heap space usage during garbage collection.

Relevance to Profiling:

  • Helps track the allocation and usage of different heap spaces (such as old, young, eden, from, and to spaces).
  • Provides insights into how the heap space is utilized during garbage collection.
  • Allows profiling and analysis of memory allocation patterns and effectiveness of garbage collection algorithms.

Fields of the PSHeapSummary event:

  • gcId: GC Identifier
  • when: The phase or level of the garbage collection when the event occurred.
  • oldSpace: Summary of the old space in the heap.

  • youngSpace: Summary of the young space in the heap.
  • edenSpace: Summary of the eden space in the heap.
  • fromSpace: Summary of the from space in the heap.
  • toSpace: Summary of the to space in the heap.

The MetaspaceAllocationFailure event in JFR (Java Flight Recorder) is used to track failures in metaspace allocation. It provides information about the class loader, hidden class loader, size, metadata type, and metaspace object type associated with the allocation failure.

This event is relevant to profiling because it allows developers to analyze and understand the reasons behind metaspace allocation failures, which can help them optimize memory usage and performance in their Java applications.

To use the MetaspaceAllocationFailure event for profiling:

  • Subscribe to the event in the JFR configuration.
  • When an allocation failure occurs, the event will be triggered and include the relevant information about the failure.
  • Use the field values of the event, such as classLoader, hiddenClassLoader, size, metadataType, and metaspaceObjectType, to analyze and diagnose the cause of the allocation failure.
  • Based on the profiling information, developers can take necessary actions, such as tuning the metaspace settings or optimizing memory usage, to address the allocation failure and improve application performance.

To use this event for profiling, you can monitor and analyze the occurrences of MetaspaceOOM events. The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in EventProvider.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The InstantEvent is a JFR event that represents an event that does not consume any time. It is used for profiling purposes to track events that occur instantaneously during program execution. Here are some key points about the InstantEvent:

  • It is an internal event in the EventProvider interface defined in the jdk.vm.ci.hotspot package.
  • It has two methods: commit() and shouldWrite().
    • commit() is used to mark the event as completed.
    • shouldWrite() determines if the event should be written to the data stream based on whether it is enabled and other factors.
  • It is intended to be extended or implemented by other classes.
  • It can be used to profile and track specific events that occur without consuming any time, such as the occurrence of a particular condition or event in the program.

The ResidentSetSize event in JFR represents the resident set size of a process, which is the amount of memory that is currently held in RAM for the process. This event is relevant for profiling to understand the memory usage of the process. The event has two fields:

  • size represents the resident set size of the process.
  • peak represents the peak value of the resident set size, which is the highest it has been during the lifetime of the process.

By analyzing the ResidentSetSize event, developers and performance engineers can gain insights into the memory consumption patterns of the application and identify potential areas for optimization or memory leaks.

NativeMemoryUsageTotal

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Memory

Total native memory usage for the JVM. Might not be the exact sum of the NativeMemoryUsage events due to timeing.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrNativeMemoryEvent.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The NativeMemoryUsageTotal event in JFR provides information about the total amount of reserved and committed memory for the JVM.

Meaning and relevance of the event to profiling:

  • reserved field: Represents the total amount of reserved bytes for the JVM. It indicates the memory that has been allocated but not yet used.
  • committed field: Represents the total amount of committed bytes for the JVM. It indicates the memory that has been allocated and can be used by the JVM.

Profiling with this event:

  • By analyzing the values of the reserved and committed fields, developers can gain insights into the memory usage of the JVM during runtime.
  • Tracking changes in these fields over time can help identify memory leak issues or excessive memory consumption in the application.
  • Comparing the values of reserved and committed with other performance metrics can provide a holistic view of the JVM's memory utilization.

Note: The mentioned code provides helper methods to send events related to different types of memory usage, allowing for detailed profiling of specific memory areas.

Configuration enabled period
default true 1000 ms
profiling true 1000 ms

Field Type Description
reserved ulong: bytes Reserved Memory Total amount of reserved bytes for the JVM
committed ulong: bytes Committed Memory Total amount of committed bytes for the JVM

The OldObjectSample event in JFR is used for profiling purposes. Its fields provide information about old objects being sampled in the heap.

  • allocationTime: Time when the object was allocated.
  • objectSize: Size of the object.
  • objectAge: Age of the object.
  • lastKnownHeapUsage: Heap usage at the time of the last garbage collection.
  • object: Identifier for the object.
  • arrayElements: Number of elements in the array if the object is an array, or -1 if it is not.
  • root: Identifier for the garbage collection root.

This event can be used to gather information about old objects in order to analyze memory allocation patterns and optimize memory usage.

ExecutionSample

default profiling startTime every chunk 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Profiling

Snapshot of a threads state

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrThreadSampler.cpp, and jfrJniMethod.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ExecutionSample event in JFR is relevant to profiling and provides information about thread execution samples. It has the following fields:

  • sampledThread: Represents the thread that was sampled.
  • stackTrace: Represents the stack trace of the thread at the time of sampling.
  • state: Represents the state of the thread at the time of sampling.

This event can be used for profiling purposes to analyze thread execution and identify performance bottlenecks. By examining the sampledThread and stackTrace fields, developers can gain insights into the execution flow and identify hotspots in the code. The state field can provide additional context about the thread's state during the sampling, such as whether it was running, suspended, or in a different state.

Overall, the ExecutionSample event is a valuable tool for profiling and optimizing applications by providing detailed information about thread execution and stack traces.

default true 20 ms
profiling true 10 ms

  • carrierThread: The thread that is being enlisted as a carrier for the continuation.

The ContinuationFreeze event in JFR is an experimental event that provides information about the freezing of a continuation. It is useful for profiling and analyzing the behavior of continuations. Invocation of Continuation.run() on a started continuation

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in continuationFreezeThaw.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ContinuationThaw event in JFR represents the thawing of frames in a continuation. It is relevant to profiling because it provides information about the thawing process and allows for analysis of stack frames.

The event has the following fields:

  • carrierThread: The thread enlisted as a carrier during the thawing process
  • continuationClass: The class of the continuation being thawed
  • interpretedFrames: The number of interpreted frames that were thawed
  • size: The size of the stack after the thawing process

It is an experimental event and can be used to analyze and profile the behavior of continuations during runtime.

The ContinuationThawFast event in JFR is relevant to profiling and provides information about fast thawing of a continuation in Java code. It is used to optimize the performance of thawing operations and reduce overhead. Some key points about this event are:

  • This event is triggered when a continuation is thawed quickly, either by thawing the whole chunk or by thawing just one frame.
  • The id field represents the ID of the thawed continuation.
  • The full field indicates whether the entire chunk was thawed or just one frame.
  • The size field specifies the size of the thawed portion in bytes.
  • It is an experimental event and may be subject to changes in future versions of JFR.

SafepointStateSynchronization

startTime duration eventThread 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Runtime / Safepoint

Synchronize run state of threads

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in safepoint.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The SafepointStateSynchronization event in JFR (Java Flight Recorder) represents the synchronization state during a safepoint operation in the Java Virtual Machine (JVM). It provides information about the threads and their states during the safepoint process, which is relevant for profiling purposes.

This event has the following fields:

  • safepointId: the identifier of the safepoint
  • initialThreadCount: the number of threads that were running at the beginning of the state check, also known as "Initial Threads"
  • runningThreadCount: the number of threads still running during the safepoint, also known as "Running Threads"
  • iterations: the number of state check iterations performed during the safepoint, also known as "Iterations"

By analyzing these fields, profiling tools can gain insights into the behavior and performance of the JVM during safepoint synchronization and identify any bottlenecks or issues that may impact the overall application performance.

default false 10 ms
profiling false 0 ms

Field Type Description
safepointId ulong Safepoint Identifier
initialThreadCount int Initial Threads The number of threads running at the beginning of state check
runningThreadCount int Running Threads The number of threads still running
iterations int Iterations Number of state check iterations

ExecuteVMOperation

default profiling startTime duration eventThread 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Runtime

Execution of a VM Operation

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in vmThread.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ExecuteVMOperation event in JFR represents the execution of a VM operation in the HotSpot JVM. This event is relevant for profiling as it provides information about the VM operation being performed and whether it occurred at a safepoint. The event has the following fields:

  • operation: Specifies the type of VM operation being executed.
  • safepoint: Indicates whether the operation occurred at a safepoint or not.
  • blocking: Specifies if the calling thread was blocked until the operation was complete.
  • caller: Identifies the thread that requested the VM operation. If the operation is non-blocking, the value will be 0 indicating that the thread is unknown.
  • safepointId: Represents the identifier of the safepoint under which the operation was completed, if applicable.

By analyzing the ExecuteVMOperation events, one can gain insights into the types of VM operations being executed, their occurrence at safepoints, and the threads involved. This information can be used to identify performance bottlenecks, analyze synchronization patterns, and optimize the JVM execution.

Configuration enabled threshold
default true 10 ms
profiling true 0 ms

Field Type Description
operation VMOperationType Operation Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
safepoint boolean At Safepoint If the operation occurred at a safepoint
blocking boolean Caller Blocked If the calling thread was blocked until the operation was complete
caller Thread Caller Thread requesting operation. If non-blocking, will be set to 0 indicating thread is unknown
safepointId ulong Safepoint Identifier The safepoint (if any) under which this operation was completed

SymbolTableStatistics

default profiling startTime duration every chunk 13 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Runtime / Tables

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The SymbolTableStatistics event in JFR provides information about the symbol table of the JVM, which is used to store string literals and class names.

Fields of the event include:

  • bucketCount: the number of buckets in the symbol table
  • entryCount: the total number of entries in the symbol table
  • totalFootprint: the total memory footprint of the symbol table and its entries
  • bucketCountMaximum: the maximum number of entries in a single bucket
  • bucketCountAverage: the average number of entries in each bucket
  • bucketCountVariance: the variance of the number of entries in the buckets
  • bucketCountStandardDeviation: the standard deviation of the number of entries in the buckets
  • insertionRate: the rate at which items have been added to the symbol table since the last event
  • removalRate: the rate at which items have been removed from the symbol table since the last event

This event is relevant for profiling because it provides insights into the memory usage and performance characteristics of the symbol table, which can be useful for optimizing memory consumption and identifying potential performance bottlenecks related to string literals and class names.

Configuration enabled period
default true 10 s
profiling true 10 s

Field Type Description
bucketCount ulong Bucket Count Number of buckets
entryCount ulong Entry Count Number of all entries
totalFootprint ulong: bytes Total Footprint Total memory footprint (the table itself plus all of the entries)
bucketCountMaximum ulong Maximum Bucket Count The maximum bucket length (entries in a single bucket)
bucketCountAverage float Average Bucket Count The average bucket length
bucketCountVariance float Bucket Count Variance How far bucket lengths are spread out from their average value
bucketCountStandardDeviation float Bucket Count Standard Deviation How far bucket lengths are spread out from their mean (expected) value
insertionRate float Insertion Rate How many items were added since last event (per second)
removalRate float Removal Rate How many items were removed since last event (per second)
