StringTableStatistics

default profiling startTime duration every chunk 13 17 21 22

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Runtime / Tables

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The StringTableStatistics event in JFR provides statistics about the String table in the JVM. This event is relevant for profiling and performance analysis. Here are the key fields of the event:

  • bucketCount: Represents the number of buckets in the String table.
  • entryCount: Indicates the total number of entries in the String table.
  • totalFootprint: Reflects the memory footprint of the String table, including both the table itself and all entries.
  • bucketCountMaximum: Represents the maximum length of a bucket, which is the number of entries in a single bucket.
  • bucketCountAverage: Represents the average length of a bucket in the String table.
  • bucketCountVariance: Indicates the variance of bucket lengths, showing how spread out they are from the average value.
  • bucketCountStandardDeviation: Represents the standard deviation of bucket lengths, indicating how far they are spread out from the mean value.
  • insertionRate: Reflects the rate at which items have been added to the String table since the last event.
  • removalRate: Indicates the rate at which items have been removed from the String table since the last event.

These statistics can be used to analyze the performance and efficiency of the String table in terms of memory usage and access patterns.

Configuration enabled period
default true 10 s
profiling true 10 s

Field Type Description
bucketCount ulong Bucket Count Number of buckets
entryCount ulong Entry Count Number of all entries
totalFootprint ulong: bytes Total Footprint Total memory footprint (the table itself plus all of the entries)
bucketCountMaximum ulong Maximum Bucket Count The maximum bucket length (entries in a single bucket)
bucketCountAverage float Average Bucket Count The average bucket length
bucketCountVariance float Bucket Count Variance How far bucket lengths are spread out from their average value
bucketCountStandardDeviation float Bucket Count Standard Deviation How far bucket lengths are spread out from their mean (expected) value
insertionRate float Insertion Rate How many items were added since last event (per second)
removalRate float Removal Rate How many items were removed since last event (per second)

The ModuleRequire event is used for profiling and captures information about module dependencies in Java Flight Recorder (JFR). Here is a concise explanation of its relevance and fields:

  • The ModuleRequire event captures information about modules that are required by other modules.
  • It is used to identify the source module that requires another module, and the required module itself.
  • The source field represents the source module that has a dependency on another module.
  • The requiredModule field represents the module that is required by the source module.

By using the ModuleRequire event, profiling tools can analyze the module dependencies within an application. This information is useful for understanding the relationships between different modules and optimizing the application's module system.

The ModuleExport event in JFR is used for profiling and captures information about module exports in an application. Here is a concise explanation of its meaning and relevance:

ThreadPark

default profiling startTime duration eventThread stackTrace 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Application

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in unsafe.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ThreadPark event in JFR represents the state of a thread being parked in the program.

Fields of the ThreadPark event:

  • parkedClass: the class on which the thread is parked
  • timeout: the timeout value for the park operation
  • until: the time until when the thread is parked
  • address: the address of the object being parked

This event can be used for profiling purposes to analyze thread behavior and identify potential performance issues related to thread synchronization and coordination.

JavaMonitorEnter

default profiling startTime duration eventThread stackTrace 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Application

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in objectMonitor.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The JFR event JavaMonitorEnter is used to track when a thread enters a Java monitor, which allows profiling and analysis of lock contention and synchronization behavior.

This event has the following relevant fields:

  • monitorClass: the class of the monitor being entered
  • previousOwner: the previous owner of the monitor
  • address: the address of the monitor object

By monitoring this event, it is possible to gain insights into the synchronization behavior of Java applications, identify potential bottlenecks and contention points, and optimize the usage of monitors to improve performance.

JavaMonitorWait

default profiling startTime duration eventThread stackTrace 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Application

Waiting on a Java monitor

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in objectMonitor.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The JavaMonitorWait event in JFR represents a thread waiting for a monitor to become available. It is relevant for profiling because it provides information about the contention for locks in the application.

Fields of the JavaMonitorWait event:

  • monitorClass: Class of the object on which the thread is waiting, referred to as the monitor class.
  • notifier: The thread that notifies the waiting thread when the monitor becomes available, referred to as the notifier thread.
  • timeout: The maximum amount of time the thread waits for the monitor to become available, referred to as the timeout.
  • timedOut: Indicates whether the waiting thread timed out while waiting for the monitor, referred to as the timed out flag.
  • address: The memory address of the object on which the thread is waiting, referred to as the monitor address.

By analyzing the JavaMonitorWait event and its fields, you can profile the application to identify potential bottlenecks or areas of contention where threads are waiting for the same monitor. This information can help in optimizing concurrency and improving overall application performance.

Configuration enabled stackTrace threshold
default true true 20 ms
profiling true true 10 ms

Field Type Description
monitorClass Class Monitor Class Class of object waited on
notifier Thread Notifier Thread Notifying Thread
timeout long: millis Timeout Maximum wait time
timedOut boolean Timed Out Wait has been timed out
address ulong: address Monitor Address Address of object waited on

profiling startTime duration eventThread stackTrace 11 17 21 22

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in synchronizer.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The JavaMonitorInflate event in JFR represents the inflation of a monitor object in Java code.

  • monitorClass field: It captures the class of the monitor object.
  • address field: It stores the memory address of the monitor object.
  • cause field: It indicates the reason for the monitor inflation.

This event is relevant for profiling as it provides insights into the occurrence and causes of monitor inflation, which can help in identifying synchronization bottlenecks and optimizing the performance of Java applications.

Category: Java Application

Allocation in new Thread Local Allocation Buffer

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in allocTracer.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ObjectAllocationInNewTLAB event in JFR (Java Flight Recorder) is used to profile memory allocation in a Thread-Local Allocation Buffer (TLAB). It provides information about the objects being allocated outside the TLAB.

Relevance of the event to profiling and its fields:

  • objectClass: This field represents the class of the allocated object. It helps identify the type of objects being allocated.
  • allocationSize: This field indicates the size of the allocation, which helps track memory usage and identify memory-intensive areas.
  • tlabSize: This field specifies the size of the TLAB, which assists in understanding TLAB usage and potential optimizations.

By analyzing the ObjectAllocationInNewTLAB events, developers can gain insights into the allocation behavior of objects outside the TLAB, identify memory-consuming objects, and optimize memory usage in the application.

ObjectAllocationSample

throttle default profiling startTime eventThread stackTrace 16 17 21 22

Category: Java Application

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrObjectAllocationSample.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ObjectAllocationSample event is used for profiling the allocation of objects in Java Flight Recorder (JFR). Here is a concise explanation of the event and its relevance to profiling:

  • The objectClass field represents the class of the allocated object. It gives information about the specific object type being allocated.
  • The weight field represents the relative weight of the sample. It indicates the allocation pressure generated by the object allocation. Aggregating the weights for a particular class, thread, or stack trace provides a statistically accurate representation of the allocation pressure.

Using the ObjectAllocationSample event for profiling:

  • By monitoring the objectClass field, you can analyze the allocation behavior of different object types, helping identify potential memory inefficiencies or excessive object creation.
  • By examining the weight field, you can measure the allocation pressure generated by specific classes, threads, or stack traces, providing insights into the impact of allocation on overall performance.

Overall, the ObjectAllocationSample event plays a crucial role in profiling object allocation behavior and identifying optimization opportunities to improve application performance.

Configuration enabled stackTrace throttle
default true true 150/s
profiling true true 300/s

Field Type Description
objectClass Class Object Class Class of allocated object
weight long: bytes Sample Weight The relative weight of the sample. Aggregating the weights for a large number of samples, for a particular class, thread or stack trace, gives a statistically accurate representation of the allocation pressure

FileForce

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 11 17 21 22

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/FileForceEvent.java

Category: Java Application

Force updates to be written to file

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in EventConfigurations.java, FileForceEvent.java, JDKEvents.java, and FileChannelImplInstrumentor.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The FileForce event is a Java Flight Recorder (JFR) event that is used for profiling file force operations in a Java application. It captures information about force updates being written to a file.

The relevance of the FileForce event to profiling and its fields are:

  • path: The full path of the file being forced to update. This field provides information about the file that is being operated on.
  • metaData: A boolean flag indicating whether the file metadata is updated during the force operation. This field helps to identify whether metadata updates are occurring during the process.

By enabling and using the FileForce event, developers can gather profiling data related to file force operations, including the path and metadata update status. This can be useful for understanding performance characteristics and optimizing file operations in Java applications.

Configuration enabled stackTrace threshold
default true true 20 ms
profiling true true 10 ms

Field Type Description
path string Path Full path of the file
metaData boolean Update Metadata Whether the file metadata is updated

SocketWrite

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 11 17 21 22

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/SocketWriteEvent.java

Category: Java Application

Writing data to a socket

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in EventConfigurations.java, SocketWriteEvent.java, JDKEvents.java, SocketChannelImplInstrumentor.java, and SocketOutputStreamInstrumentor.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The SocketWrite event in JFR represents the action of writing data to a socket. It has the following fields:

  • host: the remote host of the socket
  • address: the remote address of the socket
  • port: the remote port of the socket
  • bytesWritten: the number of bytes written to the socket

This event is relevant for profiling as it allows monitoring and analyzing socket write operations in a Java application. By capturing this event, you can gather information about the remote host and address, the port, and the amount of data written to the socket. This can help in identifying potential bottlenecks or performance issues related to socket communication.

Configuration enabled stackTrace threshold
default true true 20 ms
profiling true true 10 ms

Field Type Description
host string Remote Host
address string Remote Address
port int Remote Port
bytesWritten long: bytes Bytes Written Number of bytes written to the socket

VirtualThreadStart

startTime duration stackTrace 19 21 22

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/VirtualThreadStartEvent.java

Category: Java Application

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in VirtualThreadStartEvent.java, JDKEvents.java, VirtualThreadStartEvent.java, and VirtualThread.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The VirtualThreadStart event is a Java Flight Recorder (JFR) event that is used to record the start of a virtual thread. Here is its meaning and relevance to profiling:

  • The event is located in the jdk.jfr.events package and is categorized as a "Java Application" event.
  • It is labeled as "Virtual Thread Start" and has the JFR name jdk.VirtualThreadStart.
  • The event is a subclass of AbstractJDKEvent, which is a base class for all JFR events provided by the JDK.
  • The event has a single field:
    • javaThreadId: This field represents the thread ID of the virtual thread that has been started.

Relevance to Profiling:

  • The VirtualThreadStart event is relevant for profiling because it allows you to track and analyze the creation of virtual threads in your application.
  • By recording this event, you can gain insights into the usage and behavior of virtual threads and identify any patterns or issues related to their creation.
  • The javaThreadId field provides the specific thread ID of the virtual thread, which can be used to correlate events and analyze the execution flow of these threads.

Overall, the VirtualThreadStart event is a valuable tool for profiling and understanding the behavior of virtual threads in your Java application.

Configuration enabled stackTrace
default false true
profiling false true

Field Type Description
javaThreadId long Thread Id

The FileWrite event in JFR represents the action of writing data to a file in a Java application. It is relevant for profiling because it allows developers to track and analyze file write operations.

Fields of the FileWrite event:

  • bytesWritten: Number of bytes written to the file.

By collecting data from the FileWrite event, developers can gain insights into file write activity and potentially identify any performance bottlenecks or inefficiencies in their code related to file writing.

Reading data from a socket

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in EventConfigurations.java, SocketReadEvent.java, JDKEvents.java, SocketChannelImplInstrumentor.java, and SocketInputStreamInstrumentor.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The SocketRead event in JFR represents the reading of data from a socket in a Java application. This event is relevant for profiling and monitoring socket read operations.

Fields of the SocketRead event:

  • host: the remote host of the socket
  • address: the remote address of the socket
  • port: the remote port of the socket
  • timeout: the timeout value for the socket read operation
  • bytesRead: the number of bytes read from the socket
  • endOfStream: indicates if the end of the stream was reached during the socket read operation

By capturing and analyzing SocketRead events, you can gain insights into the performance and behavior of socket read operations in your Java application. This information can help identify bottlenecks, detect potential issues, and optimize the networking aspect of your application.

ThreadSleep

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 11 17 21 22

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/ThreadSleepEvent.java

Category: Java Application

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in ThreadSleepEvent.java, JDKEvents.java, ThreadSleepEvent.java, and Thread.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ThreadSleepEvent in JFR is an event that records when a thread is sleeping. It is relevant to profiling because it allows you to track the amount of time a thread spends sleeping, which can be useful for identifying performance issues or bottlenecks in your application.

Key points about the ThreadSleepEvent:

  • The event is categorized under "Java Application" and labeled as "Java Thread Sleep".
  • The event class is named jdk.ThreadSleep and mirrors the internal event class jdk.internal.event.ThreadSleepEvent.
  • The event has a single field time, which represents the sleep time in nanoseconds.
  • The time field is annotated with @Label("Sleep Time") and @Timespan(Timespan.NANOSECONDS).
  • To determine if the ThreadSleepEvent is enabled, you can use the isTurnedOn() method of the event class.
  • To create a new ThreadSleepEvent instance, you can use the new ThreadSleepEvent() constructor.
  • After creating an event instance, you can set the sleep time value using the time field.
  • Before a thread goes to sleep, you can call the beforeSleep() method to create a new event instance with the sleep time.
  • After the thread wakes up from sleep, you can call the afterSleep() method to commit the event.

The ThreadSleepEvent allows you to profile and analyze the sleep behavior of threads in your application. By collecting and analyzing the sleep time data, you can gain insights into the efficiency of thread synchronization and resource utilization.

default true true 20 ms
profiling true true 10 ms

Field Type Description
time long: nanos Sleep Time

Java Application Statistics

JavaThreadStatistics

default profiling startTime duration every chunk 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Application / Statistics

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The JavaThreadStatistics event in JFR provides information about the thread statistics in the Java application. This event is relevant for profiling purposes. The fields of this event include:

  • activeCount: Number of live active threads including both daemon and non-daemon threads. This field represents the count of all currently running threads in the application.
  • daemonCount: Number of live daemon threads. This field represents the count of all currently running daemon threads in the application.
  • accumulatedCount: Number of threads created and also started since the JVM start. This field represents the total number of threads created and started since the JVM started.
  • peakCount: Peak live thread count since the JVM start or when the peak count was reset. This field represents the highest number of concurrently running threads since the JVM started or since the peak count was reset.

By analyzing the values of these fields, developers can gain insights into the thread usage and behavior of their Java application, which can be useful for performance profiling and optimization.

Configuration enabled period
default true 1000 ms
profiling true 1000 ms

Field Type Description
activeCount long Active Threads Number of live active threads including both daemon and non-daemon threads
daemonCount long Daemon Threads Number of live daemon threads
accumulatedCount long Accumulated Threads Number of threads created and also started since JVM start
peakCount long Peak Threads Peak live thread count since JVM start or when peak count was reset

default profiling startTime duration every chunk 11 17 21 22

Category: Java Application / Statistics

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ClassLoaderStatistics event provides information about the class loading statistics in the Java application. It is useful for profiling and understanding the memory usage of class loaders. The fields of the event include:

  • classLoader: The specific class loader responsible for loading classes.
  • parentClassLoader: The parent class loader of the current class loader.
  • classLoaderData: A pointer to the ClassLoaderData structure in the JVM.
  • classCount: The number of loaded classes by the class loader.
  • chunkSize: The total size of all allocated metaspace chunks (each chunk has several blocks) used by the class loader.
  • blockSize: The total size of all allocated metaspace blocks (each chunk has several blocks) used by the class loader.
  • hiddenClassCount: The number of hidden classes loaded by the class loader.
  • hiddenChunkSize: The total size of all allocated metaspace chunks (each chunk has several blocks) used by the class loader for hidden classes.
  • hiddenBlockSize: The total size of all allocated metaspace blocks (each chunk has several blocks) used by the class loader for hidden classes.

By analyzing the values of these fields, developers can gain insights into the memory consumption of class loaders and identify potential memory leaks or bottlenecks in the class loading process.

default true everyChunk
profiling true everyChunk

Field Type Description
classLoader ClassLoader Class Loader Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.

classLoaderData ulong: address ClassLoaderData Pointer Pointer to the ClassLoaderData structure in the JVM
classCount long Classes Number of loaded classes
chunkSize ulong: bytes Total Chunk Size Total size of all allocated metaspace chunks (each chunk has several blocks)
blockSize ulong: bytes Total Block Size Total size of all allocated metaspace blocks (each chunk has several blocks)
hiddenClassCount long 15+ Hidden Classes Number of hidden classes
hiddenChunkSize ulong: bytes 15+ Total Hidden Classes Chunk Size Total size of all allocated metaspace chunks for hidden classes (each chunk has several blocks)

The FinalizerStatistics event in JFR provides information about the finalization process in the JVM. It is used for profiling and performance analysis. This event has the following fields:

  • finalizableClass: Represents the class that overrides the finalize method.

  • objects: Represents the number of objects on the heap that can be finalized.
  • totalFinalizersRun: Indicates the total number of finalizers that have been executed since the JVM started.

By profiling the FinalizerStatistics event, developers can gain insights into the finalization process, such as the number of objects that are candidates for finalization and the number of finalizers executed. This information can help identify any performance bottlenecks or issues related to finalization in the application.

The X509CertificateEvent is an event in JFR (Java Flight Recorder) that represents details of an X.509 certificate parsed by the JDK (Java Development Kit). It is relevant for profiling and monitoring the security aspects of certificate handling in Java applications. The event provides the following fields for profiling:

  • algorithm: The signature algorithm used in the certificate.
  • serialNumber: The serial number of the certificate.
  • subject: The subject field of the certificate.
  • issuer: The issuer field of the certificate.
  • keyType: The type of key used in the certificate.
  • keyLength: The length of the key in the certificate.
  • certificateId: The unique identifier of the certificate.
  • validFrom: The timestamp when the certificate becomes valid.
  • validUntil: The timestamp when the certificate expires.

By capturing and analyzing these fields in the X509CertificateEvent, developers can gain insights into the security aspects of their application, such as the algorithms and key lengths used in certificates, certificate lifetimes, and other relevant details.

VirtualThreadSubmitFailed

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 19 21 22

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/VirtualThreadSubmitFailedEvent.java

Category: Java Development Kit / Threading

Submit of task for virtual thread failed

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in VirtualThreadSubmitFailedEvent.java, JDKEvents.java, VirtualThreadSubmitFailedEvent.java, and VirtualThread.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The VirtualThreadSubmitFailed event in JFR (jdk.VirtualThreadSubmitFailed) is used to record when an attempt to submit a task for a virtual thread fails. It is relevant for profiling because it allows developers to analyze and diagnose failures in virtual thread submissions.

Key points about the VirtualThreadSubmitFailed event:

  • It belongs to the "Java Development Kit" and "Threading" categories.
  • The event class is VirtualThreadSubmitFailedEvent, located in the jdk.jfr.events package.
  • It extends the AbstractJDKEvent class.
  • The event has two fields:
    • javaThreadId: Represents the thread ID of the virtual thread.
    • exceptionMessage: Stores the exception message when the virtual thread submission fails.
  • The event is triggered when a RejectedExecutionException occurs during virtual thread submission.
  • To use this event for profiling, create an instance of VirtualThreadSubmitFailedEvent and set the javaThreadId and exceptionMessage fields accordingly before calling the commit() method to record the event.
  • The event can be enabled or disabled using the isEnabled() method.

Overall, the VirtualThreadSubmitFailed event helps in profiling and analyzing virtual thread submission failures by recording relevant information about the failed submission.

default true true
profiling true true

Field Type Description

The JFR ThreadCPULoad event captures the CPU load for each thread in the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) during a specific interval. It is relevant for profiling purposes as it provides information about the CPU usage of each thread in the system.

  • user: Represents the percentage of user mode CPU load for the thread.
  • system: Represents the percentage of system mode CPU load for the thread.

To use this event for profiling, you can:

  1. Retrieve the user and system fields of the event for each thread.
  2. Analyze the CPU load of the threads to identify bottlenecks or areas of high CPU usage.
  3. Compare the CPU load across different threads to understand the distribution of workload in the application.
  4. Monitor changes in the CPU load of threads over time to detect performance issues or optimizations opportunities.

Overall, the JFR ThreadCPULoad event is a valuable tool for profiling and understanding the CPU usage of threads in a Java application.

ContainerConfiguration

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 17 21 22

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/ContainerConfigurationEvent.java

Category: Operating System

A set of container specific attributes

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in ContainerConfigurationEvent.java, and JDKEvents.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ContainerConfigurationEvent is an event in Java Flight Recorder (JFR) that represents a set of container-specific attributes. It is relevant for profiling and monitoring containerized applications.

The event has the following fields:

  • containerType: Container type information
  • cpuSlicePeriod: Length of the scheduling period for processes within the container
  • cpuQuota: Total available run-time allowed during each scheduling period for all tasks in the container
  • cpuShares: Relative weighting of processes within the container used for prioritizing the scheduling of processes across all containers running on a host
  • effectiveCpuCount: Number of effective processors that this container has available to it
  • memorySoftLimit: Hint to the operating system that allows groups to specify the minimum required amount of physical memory
  • memoryLimit: Maximum amount of physical memory that can be allocated in the container
  • swapMemoryLimit: Maximum amount of physical memory and swap space, in bytes, that can be allocated in the container
  • hostTotalMemory: Total memory of the host running the container

By capturing this event, you can obtain information about the configuration and resource allocation of a container, which can be used for performance analysis and troubleshooting in containerized environments.

Configuration enabled period
default true beginChunk
profiling true beginChunk

Field Type Description
containerType string Container Type Container type information
cpuSlicePeriod long: microseconds CPU Slice Period Length of the scheduling period for processes within the container
cpuQuota long: microseconds CPU Quota Total available run-time allowed during each scheduling period for all tasks in the container
cpuShares long CPU Shares Relative weighting of processes with the container used for prioritizing the scheduling of processes across all containers running on a host
effectiveCpuCount long Effective CPU Count Number of effective processors that this container has available to it
memorySoftLimit long: bytes Memory Soft Limit Hint to the operating system that allows groups to specify the minimum required amount of physical memory
memoryLimit long: bytes Memory Limit Maximum amount of physical memory that can be allocated in the container
swapMemoryLimit long: bytes Memory and Swap Limit Maximum amount of physical memory and swap space, in bytes, that can be allocated in the container
hostTotalMemory long: bytes 20+ Container Host Total Memory Total memory of the host running the container

The ContainerCPUThrottling event in JFR provides information related to CPU throttling in containerized environments. It is used for profiling purposes.

Fields in the ContainerCPUThrottling event: -cpuElapsedSlices: Number of time-slice periods that have elapsed if a CPU quota has been set up for the container. -cpuThrottledSlices: Number of time-slice periods that the CPU has been throttled or limited due to exceeding the CPU quota. -cpuThrottledTime: Total time duration in nanoseconds that the CPU has been throttled or limited due to exceeding the CPU quota.

cpuThrottledSlices long CPU Throttled Slices Number of time-slice periods that the CPU has been throttled or limited due to exceeding CPU quota
cpuThrottledTime long: nanos CPU Throttled Time Total time duration, in nanoseconds, that the CPU has been throttled or limited due to exceeding CPU quota

Category: Operating System / Memory

Container memory usage related information

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in ContainerMemoryUsageEvent.java, and JDKEvents.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

  • The ContainerMemoryUsage event provides information related to the memory usage of a container.
  • It is relevant for profiling because it allows measurement and analysis of memory-related metrics within a container.
  • The event has the following fields:
    • memoryFailCount: Number of times that user memory requests in the container have exceeded the memory limit.
    • memoryUsage: Amount of physical memory, in bytes, currently allocated in the container.
    • swapMemoryUsage: Amount of physical memory and swap space, in bytes, currently allocated in the container.
  • These fields provide valuable insights into the memory utilization and performance of containerized applications, allowing for efficient memory profiling and analysis.

Configuration enabled period
default true 30 s
profiling true 30 s

Field Type Description
memoryFailCount long Memory Fail Count Number of times that user memory requests in the container have exceeded the memory limit
memoryUsage long: bytes Memory Usage Amount of physical memory, in bytes, that is currently allocated in the current container
swapMemoryUsage long: bytes Memory and Swap Usage Amount of physical memory and swap space, in bytes, that is currently allocated in the current container

ContainerCPUUsage

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 17 21 22

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/ContainerCPUUsageEvent.java

Category: Operating System / Processor

Container CPU usage related information

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in ContainerCPUUsageEvent.java, and JDKEvents.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ContainerCPUUsage event is a Java Flight Recorder (JFR) event that provides information about the CPU usage of tasks running in a container.

Fields of the event:

  • cpuTime: Represents the aggregate time consumed by all tasks in the container. It indicates the total CPU time utilized by the tasks.
  • cpuUserTime: Represents the aggregate user time consumed by all tasks in the container. It indicates the time spent by the tasks in user mode.
  • cpuSystemTime: Represents the aggregate system time consumed by all tasks in the container. It indicates the time spent by the tasks in kernel mode.

Relevance to profiling:

  • The ContainerCPUUsage event is relevant for profiling the CPU usage of tasks running in a container.
  • By analyzing the values of cpuTime, cpuUserTime, and cpuSystemTime, you can understand the resource utilization of the containerized tasks and identify any potential bottlenecks or performance issues.
  • This event can be used to monitor and optimize the CPU usage of containers in order to improve the overall efficiency and performance of the application.

Configuration enabled period
default true 30 s
profiling true 30 s

Field Type Description
cpuTime long: nanos CPU Time Aggregate time consumed by all tasks in the container
cpuUserTime long: nanos CPU User Time Aggregate user time consumed by all tasks in the container
cpuSystemTime long: nanos CPU System Time Aggregate system time consumed by all tasks in the container

ContainerIOUsage

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 17 21 22

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/ContainerIOUsageEvent.java

Category: Operating System / File System

Container IO usage related information

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in ContainerIOUsageEvent.java, and JDKEvents.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ContainerIOUsage JFR event provides information about the IO usage of a container. It is relevant for profiling and monitoring purposes.

Fields:

  • serviceRequests: Represents the number of block IO requests made by the container to the disk.
  • dataTransferred: Represents the number of block IO bytes transferred to/from the disk by the container.

This event can be used to gather IO usage statistics and analyze the performance of containerized applications.

Configuration enabled period
default true 30 s
profiling true 30 s

Field Type Description
serviceRequests long Block IO Request Count Number of block IO requests to the disk that have been issued by the container
dataTransferred long: bytes Block IO Transfer Number of block IO bytes that have been transferred to/from the disk by the container

ProcessStart

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 15 17 21 22

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/ProcessStartEvent.java

Category: Operating System

Operating system process started

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in ProcessStartEvent.java, JDKEvents.java, ProcessBuilder.java, and ProcessStartEvent.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ProcessStart event is used to track the start of an operating system process. It is relevant to profiling because it allows monitoring and analysis of process creation in an application.

Fields of the ProcessStart event:

  • pid: Represents the process ID (PID) of the started process.
  • directory: Represents the directory in which the process was started.
  • command: Represents the command used to start the process.

Using the ProcessStart event for profiling:

  • By monitoring this event, profiling tools can track the start time and characteristics of processes within an application.
  • The pid field can be used to identify and trace specific processes.
  • The directory field provides information about the working directory of the process.
  • The command field contains the command used to start the process, allowing analysis of the execution environment.

Overall, the ProcessStart event is valuable for profiling purposes as it provides insight into the creation and properties of operating system processes within an application.

Configuration enabled stackTrace
default true true
profiling true true

Field Type Description
pid long Process Id
directory string Directory Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
command string Command Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
